FB01_01: I want to make clear that my resistance for preregistration comes from the fact that neuroimaging data are complex (and our understanding of the brain limited), and the research questions that we address are always against the limits of what current analysis tools are capable of doing. Consequently, getting answers to questions mostly requires fine-tuning methods, developing new approaches, bringing in other tools, etc. While this creates the risk of biasing results, this risk can easily be minimalized by openness in reporting on a study, e.g. showing that results do not depend on specific parameters and pre-processing steps, that they are selective (or not) for particular structures etc. While preregistrations imposes restriction on exploratory analysis, it also constrains the creativity that is at the basis of progress in science. And it leads to terrible papers, where to much text is spent on explaining the preregistered content and the justifications for deviating from them.

FB01_01: Asking other people for things is very easy. The actual work others have to do for that request is not easy or trivial. "Share your data" sound nice and no one would be against it in principle, but in reality it places a significant extra burden on the authors. Authors have already spent massive resources getting a paper out the door. Adding more burdens on authors by requiring data sharing is a nontrivial decision and has significant costs for the authors, including those in preparing proper documentation. Whether the data will be used by anyone at all, and how long a given repository will last are other questions. In 2006 I shared a full fMRI dataset, and spend an entire week of full time work preparing that data and documenting various scripts and other notes. I don't think a single person has used it and the journal repository disappeared as far as I know. It is always easy to ask other people to spend more money, more time, more resources, when it does not cost anything to you personally. It would be great if all fMRI datasets were available with proper and detailed documentation to everyone, but I don't want to spend more and more, thank you.

FB01_01:
I have a lot of problems with how the field goes about open science these days. Transparency is nice, but we seem to be willing to sacrifice part of our creativity through forced standardization. That is a bad idea and will create a less creative science, a problem that is bigger than the one that gets solved. 
We -as a community- are on the wrong track when it comes to open publishing, data sharing, code availability preregistration etc. The basic tenets on which these ideas are founded are idealistic and admirable, but as currently executed this risks creating an unfairer and less creative science, not actually a more equitable and faster advancing one.
Solving these problems piece by piece is the worst possible outcome. only a concerted effort that is lead - and financed(!) by the major national funding agencies can advance this without the side-effects being more important than the original problem.
The way the survey asks its questions makes me think that when it comes to "open" science, I agree on almost nothing with the authors of the survey and has me wondering about their biases.

It is unethical: Most data is collected with the explicit or implicit assumption by the data provider (participant) that the data is treated confidentially. Sharing the data on a repository (even with restricted access, but that can be easily hacked) is a major breach of this confidentially agreement. This holds true even if there is an line in the consent form that forces the participant to consent in a data sharing scheme, because neither the participant nor the researcher (data collector / sharer) can anticiipate what type of mis-use will be done with the data.
FB01_01:
Unfortunately, the questionnaire does not address a major problem with pre-registered studies, which is: Pre-registration is only meaningful for purely confirmatory studies. Purely confirmatory studies are only meaningful when there is a strong hypothesis and the goal of the confirmatory study is to confirm this hypothsis. This is the case in 'clinical trials' in which the hypothesis is that the medication (or treatment) is better than no treatment or alternative treatments.
However, in basic science the main goal is to produce novel insights. As of this, purely confirmatory studies are more or less useless and a waste of time and (societal) ressources. One might object, that replication is a fundamental component of solid science. I agree that replication even across resarch groups is fundamentally important. However, there are much better, smarter, time-, and ressource-saving ways to replicate research findings than be pre-registration. The best way is to conduct a new study with several conditions. One condition that is meant to replicate previous findings and another that is meant to producing novel findings.
Hence, I am extremely disappointed by the current pre-registration schemes. It does not solve the problem of poor scientific conduct, but instead wastes a lot of time and ressources. This time and ressources would be much better invested in good education for self-critical research.
